I don't think that this is going to be always true? Imagine that the water is saturated with salt. Some water evaporates, the salt mass fraction exceeds equilibrium, so some precipitation occurs. However, there is still liquid, gas and now solid.
I think before you try and run a simulation, you should makes some unit tests to ensure that things are working correctly - a learn to walk before you run approach. I remember doing these for brine+co2 - they are tedious but did enable me to find all of the bugs. See https://github.com/idaholab/moose/blob/next/modules/porous_flow/unit/src/PorousFlowBrineCO2Test.C for example.
You can run the unit tests by going to moose/modules/unit and running make, then run_tests

The script does need to be updated, but I believe that the falcon name pattern is still correct (e.g. r1i3n4).
You will run this script from the headnode. It runs qstat to get back the nodes for your job and then logs into each on and gets a stack trace for you (using the "PSTACK_BINARY" you've indicated). It then writes all of the stack traces to a file on the head node and attempts to bin them. Note, it doesn't have any intelligence built in so you have to rerun the script multiple times with different values of "stacks" (e.g. ./find_hung_processes.py -s 10). It'll attempt to just keep the 10 stack frames from each trace and then match them up (throwing out things like memory addresses). If you find a situation where most of your processes are in one location and one or a few are in another, that indicates a logic bug where your processes have taken divergent paths and then gotten stuck on a collective operation.
@GiudGiud's advice also works, but you might not see the issue when you are looking at just one stack trace. You really need to look at all (or most) to see why maybe just a few ranks took a different path.

